Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Crisis Intervention Worker Lethbridge , AB Description Crisis Intervention Worker The Lethbridge Public Library proudly acknowledges that we are located at the heart of Siksikaitsitapi (Blackfoot) Territory, home of Kainai, Piikani, Siksika and Amskapi Piikani (Montana, USA) First Nations. Lethbridge is also located within the Métis Nation of Alberta, Region III. Are you a caring and compassionate person with an in-depth knowledge of trauma-informed holistic care and a passion for supporting vulnerable populations’ service needs? Are you committed to meeting people where they are at from a place of empathy and non-judgment? Are you an expert in systems navigation and proficient at connecting people to meaningful resources? Do you enjoy sharing your expertise with other professionals and staff? The Lethbridge Public Library wants you!We are seeking a full time Crisis Intervention Worker to join the Information Services team to better meet the needs of vulnerable and marginalized populations, and to ensure that all library patrons are able to access services in safe and respectful ways. You will have the opportunity to develop and maintain relationships with library patrons and community organizations, to share your professional expertise with other library staff, and to improve equitable access to low-barrier services. Working from the Main Branch, the Crisis Intervention Worker will: Connect with members of vulnerable and marginalized populations to understand and meet community needs, Assist the library’s contracted security staff to address all patron behavioural concerns from a low-barrier and restorative justice-based service model, Identify potential crisis situations before they develop, providing a preventative presence toward the maintenance of a calm and supportive library environment, Provide superior de-escalation and crisis intervention supports, with a focus on meaningful relationships and positive rapport building, Utilize their extensive knowledge of Indigenous ways of being and knowing, intergenerational trauma, and the Residential School systems in providing culturally sensitive supports, Develop and maintain relationships with relevant community organizations, Be comfortable working with people who use drugs and alcohol, and have experience providing overdose response interventions as necessary, Develop and deliver staff training regarding best practice in service provision to vulnerable and marginalized populations. Qualifications: The ideal candidate has demonstrated experience working in positive behaviour management with vulnerable and marginalized populations including people who use drugs (PWUD) and unhoused persons; an in-depth knowledge of Indigenous culture and history; is experienced in assessing community needs; has excellent relationship building skills; and possesses superior communication and organizational skills. The successful candidate must have an in-depth understanding of the social determinants of health, exhibit a high degree of empathy, and be comfortable responding to a variety of possible crisis situations (including but not limited to mental health crises, verbal or physical disagreements, intoxication and/or overdose, sexual health, and intimate partner violence). What do you need to bring to this position? You will need: A minimum of an undergraduate degree in a related field of study (Social Work, Addictions, Sociology, Indigenous Studies, Psychology, etc) At least two years of related recent experience working directly in a frontline capacity with vulnerable and marginalized populations Excellent relationship building skills Significant knowledge of the Indigenous community, including cultural protocols, histories, traditions and issues Ability to assess community interests and needs, and to plan services accordingly, in keeping with the Library’s strategic direction Ability to work effectively with patrons of all age levels and backgrounds Ability to work independently and demonstrate initiative and problem solving Demonstrated decision making skills and the ability to exercise good judgment Ability to communicate effectively in oral and written English Current First Aid certification will be considered an asset Current Non-Violent Crisis Prevention and Intervention certification will be considered an asset Current Suicide Intervention certification will be considered an asset Self-identification as a member of a First Nations, Metis, or Inuit community and/or fluency in Indigenous language(s) will be considered an asset This term position has an expected end date of July 31, 2024, with possibility for extension. This position will be working at the Main Branch and will report to the Manager: Information Services. Hours of Work: 75 hours bi-weekly, including evening and weekend hours. Compensation: In accordance with the current Collective Agreement with CUPE Local 70 (Library Employees), the salary range for this position is $32.19 to $35.68 hourly plus 4% vacation pay. (Under Review) This posting will close July 16, 2023. The Library thanks all interested applicants. Only those individuals selected for interviews will be contacted.To apply: https://tre.tbe.taleo.net/tre01/ats/careers/v2/viewRequisition?org=COLBRIDGE&amp;cws=42&amp;rid=2012 The Lethbridge Public Library recognizes and values the diversity of our community and those we employ. We are committed to advancing reconciliation in our community, as well as ensuring diversity, equity and inclusion in our workforce. We encourage self-identifying Indigenous applicants (First Nation, Métis and Inuit), as well as those from historically underrepresented groups to apply. Compensation 32.19 - 35.68 Closes: 16 July, 2023 Lethbridge Public Library Lethbridge , AB Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = 